english:
  title: Record of the Restoration of Yanyeong Seonsa Temple in Gangneung Prefecture, Goryeo
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In the autumn of the gengchen year of Zhiyuan, Park, formerly Director of Ceremonials at the National Academy, came to bid me farewell as he departed to govern Ninghai. He spoke to me, saying: "In the past, during the jiazi year of Taiding, I buried my mother north of Gangneung Castle. After the funeral rites were complete, I wished to establish a temple to pray for her spiritual salvation. Near the grave, I discovered the ruins of an ancient temple called Yanyeong. I have since undertaken its restoration, and only now has it been completed. There is a hall to enshrine the Buddha, quarters for the monks to dwell, and structures nearby for the Saint Monk. The timber frames above and the rooms below are neither extravagant nor shabby. As I have no sons and my years grow few, I shall donate all my possessions—slaves, fields, and lands—to maintain the temple in perpetuity, that it may become a place for cultivating the spirit and blessing the realm. Observing the world today, I see how the greedy scramble over every small fortune, seizing others' fields of merit for their own gain, leaving many temples with Buddhas covered in dust and courtyards choked with thorns. I grieve at this. I hope you, a man of letters, might record the full account of this temple's founding and inscription it upon stone, that it may serve as a warning to those who come after and endure forever. Moreover, there are four miraculous occurrences. Can you record them?"

    I replied: "Certainly." Then I inquired into these four wonders he spoke of.

    "When we first excavated the earth, we discovered bronze vessels and implements for incense—ancient in design, bearing names and numbered, yet unmarked by any inscription. The cauldrons with their lids appeared as though newly cast. This was the first wonder.

    "The temple had no well, and monks suffered greatly fetching water from afar. The land was high and parched, beyond what human effort could remedy. Yet one day, after quietly praying to the Buddha and beginning to dig, before we had gone even a man's length, a clear spring surged forth. This was the second wonder.

    "In the spring of the guiyou year, my father passed. I had a bronze Ksitigarbha Bodhisattva cast to honor the Buddha's grace. When the molten metal was being poured, a great rain came with fierce wind, yet suddenly the sky cleared, allowing the work to be completed with ease. This was the third wonder.

    "The following year, in yihai, fire swept through the hills and spread toward our ancestral burial grounds. The pines and junipers nearly burned to ash with no means to save them. In my grief and prayer to the Buddha, heaven turned the wind, and the flames were at last extinguished. This was the fourth wonder.

    "All who have witnessed these four events marvel at them. They say: could this be anything but the fruit of past karma and the power of filial devotion?"

    I reflected upon this: The Buddha holds compassion as his heart and salvation as his work. When a person is steadfast in righteousness and filial piety, his response is as certain as shadow follows form and echo follows sound. Park has exhausted all his strength and sincerity in serving his parents in life and in death. Yet finding this insufficient, he has turned to the Buddha to offer blessings to the spirit realm, sparing no effort. How natural, then, that such wonders should manifest! Should I not record this?

    Those who dwell in this temple in ages to come must understand that Park's intention was devoted entirely to the longevity of the ruler and the good fortune of the realm, his urgency centered upon filial piety and the benefit of all beings. Let them prevent contention over the temple's property and maintain it faithfully through the seasons. Let them read my record and understand.

    Park's name was Cheng, a man of Gangneung. He first gained renown for his talents and was recommended for office, passing the civil examination. Throughout his service, he earned a reputation for integrity and ability, rising through ranks to the position of Third Rank Official.

    Gangneung, in the days of Silla, was called the Kingdom of Rui or the Kingdom of Iron; in other names, it was known as Taoyuan Frontier or Northern Beach Capital. When it entered our nation, it became Myeongju. Now it has been elevated to the status of Prefecture, becoming the foremost city of the eastern realm.

    Recorded on the sixteenth day of the ninth month in the sixth year of Zhiyuan.
  footnotes:
    - 'Yanyeong Seonsa Temple: A Buddhist temple in Gangneung whose restoration is the subject of this record, notable for the miraculous events attributed to its completion.'
    - 'Park Cheng: A Goryeo official of high rank who undertook the temple''s restoration as a memorial to his deceased mother and as a means of ensuring spiritual merit.'
    - 'The four miracles: These represent the convergence of filial piety and Buddhist grace—the discovery of ancient bronze vessels, the miraculous appearance of a spring, the successful casting of the Ksitigarbha statue despite adverse weather, and the turning of a wildfire away from the ancestral burial grounds.'
    - 'Saint Monk (聖僧): Likely refers to a revered Buddhist teacher or elder monk given special quarters within the temple complex.'
    - 'Lee Gok (李穀): A Goryeo literatus and official who recorded this account, endorsing both Park Cheng''s virtue and the philosophical harmony between filial devotion and Buddhist practice.'
